Orbilium: one of the masters at Rome, to whose lessons Horace was taken by his father (S. 1. 6. 76-82). According to Suetonius he was a native of Beneventum who, aster serving for a time in the army, taught for several years in his native town, and came to Rome when fifty years of age in the consulship of Cicero (63 B.c.), where he taught maiore fama qnam emolumento. He died in poverty when nearly a hundred years of age. For his severity towards his pupils, see Intr. i. dictare: i.e. that the pupils might learn it by heart, cf. 1. 1. 55 ; 1. 18. 13. 72. exactis, ‘perfectly finished,’ properly of works of art. Cf. Ov.
